Hari’s Comments

  1. Avoid printing out entire vectors since their outputs will take up a lot of space (unique(flights$arr_delay)). Moreover, a bunch of numbers on the screen does give the reader any further insights.

  2. Consider removing groups with low number of observations from consideration since they could skew your results

  3. Based on your analysis there seems to be a relationship between distance and delays with shorter flights being more delayed. Why is this? Explore this further.

  4. Consider cutting continous variables like distance in intervals (look at cut_*() set of function under ggplot)

  5. Create a single dataset for weather + flights and use it for all the weather based analysis instead of creating separate ones each time.
  6. Use snake_case for naming your variables.
  7. Explain what is happening in each chart and your logic for trying something out. For instance, you are interested in precip vs delay because xyz.
  8. Another way to look at this would be to consider extreme values of delay and see the relationship between that and the explainatory variable.
  9. Take logs when you have a skewed variable (that spans a large range) (check out scale_x_log10())

  10. Make things more attractive

flights %>%

It looks like distance falls as arrival delay increases, except (perhaps) at LaGuardia. A little weird. The segmentation of origin I did is a bit random.

NEW WORK. I’m curious if shorter flights having higher arrival delay might be because highly delayed longer flights accelerate to reduce their delay on arrival. Let’s see. I will calculate mean speed by dividing distance by airtime and graph it against departure delay.

flights %>% 
    filter(!is.na(distance) & !is.na(air_time)) %>% 
    group_by(distance, dep_delay) %>% 
    summarise(meanSpeed = mean(distance, na.rm = T)/mean(air_time, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(meanSpeed, y = dep_delay)) +
     geom_point() +
     geom_smooth(method = lm)

Hari comment

I don’t understand the logic behind the groups you have used here. Could you spell that out i.e. explain what the code is doing?

If you are trying to argue that arrival delay is reduced by speed then one way to study that would to compare speed with to time saved in air (dep_delay - arr_delay) to show the obvious link between the two.

flights %>% 
  mutate(time_saved = dep_delay - arr_delay,
         speed = distance / air_time) %>% 
  filter(dep_delay > 0 & !is.na(speed)) %>% 
  group_by(speed) %>% 
  summarise(time_saved = mean(time_saved)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = speed, y = time_saved)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

NA

The next argument seems to be that speed and distance are somewhow related i.e. shorter flights are slower (on top of giving you less time to make up the departure delays). See below.

flights %>% 
  group_by(distance) %>% 
  summarise(mean_speed = mean(distance, na.rm = T) / mean(air_time, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  filter(!is.na(mean_speed) & distance < 3000) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = distance, y = mean_speed)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess")

This also seems to be true. This might be because of the types of planes that fly short distances.

Next follow up task for JW to investigate: Are certain types of planes faster than others? Do slower planes tend to fly shorter distances?

Here we see some positive correlation between mean airspeed and departure delay. If this relationship dissapears when we look at arrival delay, this is evidence that the reason shorter flights have more arrival delay might be in part that speed erases delay on longer flights.

flights %>% 
    filter(!is.na(distance) & !is.na(air_time)) %>% 
    group_by(distance, arr_delay) %>% 
    summarise(meanSpeed = mean(distance, na.rm = T)/mean(air_time, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(meanSpeed, y = arr_delay)) +
     geom_point() +
     geom_smooth(method = lm)

NA

Sure enough, mean speed is somewhat negatively correlated with arrival delay! Clearly, speed can be used to erase flight delay, allowing longer flights to have less delay.

flights %>% 
    filter(!is.na(tailnum)) %>% 
    group_by(month, day, tailnum) %>% 
    summarise(nLegs = n(),
              meanDistance = mean(distance, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    arrange(desc(nLegs))

SECTION TWO: Precip and Departure Delay

Hypothesis Two: there is a relationship between Precip in weather and Departure Delay.

B-1: Let’s make our dataset. Right now, Precip and flights are separated. We’ll join them, then graph precipitation vs mean departure delay.

Preciptest <- flights %>%
  select(time_hour, origin, dep_delay) %>% 
  left_join(
    x = .,
    y = weather,
    by = c("origin", "time_hour"))
Preciptest %>% 
  group_by(precip, origin) %>% 
  summarise(meandepdelayQ201 = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  arrange(meandepdelayQ201) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(precip, y = meandepdelayQ201)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm)

Looks like precipitation increases mean depature delay. Let’s wrap the graph by origin. Again, I’m scaling x-axis based on the x-values available.

It seems that the relationship remains true across airports. What else can we facet wrap?

Preciptest %>% 
  group_by(precip, carrier) %>% 
  summarise(meandepdelayQ201 = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  arrange(meandepdelayQ201) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(precip, y = meandepdelayQ201)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = lm) +
  facet_wrap(~ carrier, scales = "free_x")

Interesting and a bit hard to parse, but the relationship certainly varies by carrier.
